# Command readelf

## What does this command do:

readelf is a command-line tool used to display detailed information about ELF (Executable and Linkable Format) files on Unix-like systems. It is a core part of the GNU Binutils package

## Installed from

For Fedora install using: sudo dnf install binutils
For Raspberry Pi install using: sudo apt install binutils
For Mac install using: brew install binutils  # installs as greadelf; readelf is not natively available on macOS

## Command path

For Fedora run: /usr/bin/readelf
For Raspberry Pi run: /usr/bin/readelf
For Mac run: $(brew --prefix)/bin/greadelf  # note: not useful on Apple Silicon; ELF is a Linux/Unix binary format

## Command documentation

Docs can be found at https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man1/readelf.1.html

## Command options

# Display all information (equivalent to -h -l -S -s -r -d -V -A -I)
readelf -a <elf-file>

# Display ELF file header
readelf -h <elf-file>

# Display program headers (segments)
readelf -l <elf-file>
readelf --program-headers <elf-file>

# Display section headers
readelf -S <elf-file>
readelf --section-headers <elf-file>

# Display all headers (equivalent to -h -l -S)
readelf -e <elf-file>

# Display symbol table
readelf -s <elf-file>
readelf --syms <elf-file>

# Display dynamic symbol table
readelf --dyn-syms <elf-file>

# Display relocations
readelf -r <elf-file>

# Display dynamic section
readelf -d <elf-file>

# Display note sections
readelf -n <elf-file>

# Display version sections
readelf -V <elf-file>

# Display architecture-specific information
readelf -A <elf-file>

# Demangle symbol names (gnu-v3, java, gnat, dlang, rust)
readelf -s -C <elf-file>
readelf -s --demangle=rust <elf-file>

# Hex dump of a section (by name or index)
readelf -x .rodata <elf-file>
readelf -x 3 <elf-file>

# String dump of a section
readelf -p .rodata <elf-file>

# Dump DWARF debug info
readelf -w <elf-file>                 # all DWARF sections
readelf -wi <elf-file>                # .debug_info only
readelf -wl <elf-file>                # raw line table
readelf -wL <elf-file>                # decoded line table
readelf -wa <elf-file>                # abbreviations
readelf -wf <elf-file>                # frame info
readelf -wF <elf-file>                # frame info (interpreted)

# Display histogram of bucket list lengths
readelf -I <elf-file>

# Display unwind information
readelf -u <elf-file>

# Display archive index
readelf -c <archive.a>

# Wide output (do not truncate at 80 chars)
readelf -W -s <elf-file>

# Display section groups
readelf -g <elf-file>

# Display section details
readelf -t <elf-file>

# Enable lint/warning checks
readelf -L <elf-file>

# Read options from a file
readelf @options.txt <elf-file>
